# Gogo Forms, Templates, Static, And Cross-Cutting Rules

Use this rule when changing forms, templates, static files, uploads, fixtures,
cache, email, messages, i18n, health checks, observability, or signals.

Framework module: `github.com/cybersaksham/gogo`.

## Forms

- Use Gogo forms, widgets, formsets, model forms, field validation, and error
  handling for HTML form workflows.
- Form coverage includes scalar fields, choices, required/optional validation,
  structured field and non-field errors, widgets, form binding, cleaned data,
  formsets, model field mapping, model form save with commit control, readonly
  and localized fields, include/exclude lists, labels, help text, and uniqueness
  hooks.
- Keep form validation close to user input boundaries.
- Put reusable domain validation in services or model validation helpers when
  APIs, admin, and tasks also need it.

## Templates

- Keep project templates in `templates/`.
- Keep app templates under each app's `templates/<app>/` directory.
- Use the Gogo template engine, tags, filters, inheritance, and context helpers.
- Template coverage includes template loaders, project/app/framework template
  precedence, context processors, request/user/messages/CSRF/static/media
  context helpers, safe strings, date/default/length/join/pluralize/linebreaks
  filters, and Django-compatible helper behavior.
- Avoid embedding secrets, credentials, or environment-specific values in
  templates.

## Static Files And Uploads

- Keep project static assets in `static/` and app assets under each app's
  `static/<app>/` directory.
- Use Gogo static collection and file storage APIs for deployed assets.
- Static coverage includes finders, duplicate reporting, hashed filenames,
  manifests, collection, and static mount helpers. File coverage includes local
  storage, safe filename normalization, memory uploads, temporary uploads,
  chunked uploads, size limits, and traversal protection.
- Keep uploaded media under `media/` locally and out of Git.
- Validate file uploads by size, content type, extension, storage path, and
  authorization requirements.

## Fixtures, Cache, Email, Messages, I18n, Signals

- Use Gogo fixtures for import/export workflows.
- Use cache backends through Gogo cache APIs; namespace keys by app/domain.
- Use Gogo email backends and message objects; never hard-code credentials.
- Use Gogo messages for user-facing request messages.
- Keep i18n language/timezone settings centralized in settings.
- Use signals for cross-cutting notifications, not as hidden business logic.
- Cache coverage includes local, dummy, file, database, Redis, and
  memcached-style APIs with get, set, add, delete, touch, increment, decrement,
  many-key operations, key prefixing, versions, and cleanup.
- Email coverage includes message headers, recipients, alternatives,
  attachments, MIME rendering, console, dummy, file, memory, and SMTP backends.
- Health and observability coverage belongs to the `health` and `observability`
  packages and should be wired at project boundaries, not hidden inside app
  services.

## Contrib Apps

- Use contrib packages for sites, redirects, flatpages, sitemaps, syndication,
  humanize filters, staff-only admin docs, PostgreSQL helpers, and GIS/PostGIS
  helpers.
- Site-aware contrib behavior should install `gogo.contrib.sites` before
  redirects, flatpages, sitemaps, or syndication features that depend on the
  current site.
- Run `gogo check` after changing installed contrib apps or middleware order.
